BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:JOIN US FOR OUR APRIL BOOK CLUB: VIGIL
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260413T183000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260414T203000
UID:bm-4834820260413@flyingbooks.ca
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://cdn1.bookmanager.com/i/8102716/1_copy.jp
 g?cb=1773330715
DESCRIPTION:[Book Club]\nWe can't wait to discuss George Saunder's new nov
 el\,\nVigil\nwith you at Flying Books at Neverland\, our 371 Queen St. W. 
 location.\nBook club ticket price includes:\n- a glass of wine (or other b
 everage of your choice)\n- a discussion with moderator Lee Suksi\n- and a 
 $20.00 credit towards the book of your choice.\nGET YOUR TICKETS HERE\nAn 
 electric novel from the #1\nNew York Times\nbest-selling\, Booker Prize-wi
 nning author of\nLincoln in the Bardo\n\;\nVigil\ntakes place at the bedsi
 de of an oil company CEO in the twilight hours of his life\, as he is ferr
 ied from this world into the next.\n\nWith the wisdom\, playfulness\, and 
 explosive imagination we’ve come to expect\, George Saunders takes on th
 e gravest issues of our time—the menace of corporate greed\, the toll of
  capitalism\, the environmental perils of progress—and\, in the process\
 , spins a tale that encompasses life and death\, good and evil\, and the t
 horny question of absolution.\nJoin us on Monday\, April 13th or Tuesday\,
  April 14th for a drink and buzzy conversation.  Use your book credit tow
 ards our next book club pick\, or anything in the store.\nImportant to kno
 w:\nTicket price includes HST and fees.\nThe $20 book credit is only usabl
 e on the night of attendance and is non-refundable and non-transferrable.\
 nThe glass of wine is also only offered on the night of the event. ID requ
 ired.\nDue to our limited space\, book club tickets are only refundable wi
 th 7 days' notice.
LOCATION:Flying Books at Neverland\, 371 Queen St. W.
URL:https://flyingbooks.ca/events
X-SOURCE:Flying Books
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:JOIN US FOR THE LAUNCH OF THE FALL-DOWN EFFECT BY LIZ JOHNSTON
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260421T183000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260421T200000
UID:bm-4698720260421@flyingbooks.ca
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://cdn1.bookmanager.com/i/8102716/Liz_J_Tor
 onto_Launch_Poster_final_.png?cb=1771645173
DESCRIPTION:[Book Launch]\nBook*hug Press and Flying Books present the Tor
 onto launch of\nThe Fall-Down Effect b\ny Liz Johnston. Liz will be in con
 versation with Khalida Venus Hassan. Featuring guest readers Phillip Dwigh
 t Morgan and Ana Rodriguez Machado. Books will be for sale\, and the auth
 or will be signing.\nExploring protest\, climate change\, and fractured fa
 mily relationships\, Liz Johnston's eagerly anticipated debut novel\,\nThe
  Fall-Down Effect\,\nasks what we really owe people in our lives when we a
 re fighting for a greater cause.\nAs a child in the late 1980s\, Fern is t
 he wild heart of her tree-hugging family-quick-tempered and yearning to sp
 end every minute in the woods of the small Pacific Northwest logging town 
 where they live. She is also most like her environmental activist mother\,
  Lynn\, who chafes against the demands of motherhood and yearns for the pr
 otests of her youth. As tensions escalate\, Lynn leaves her partner\, Tom\
 , and their three children\, telling herself she will devote her life more
  fully to fighting for the earth.\nLiz Johnston grew up in Revelstoke\, B
 .C.\, and now lives and writes in Toronto. Her essays and\nshort stories h
 ave appeared in\nPoets & Writers\, The Fiddlehead\, The Humber Literary\
 nReview\,\nand\nGrain\,\namong other publications. She is an editor of\nBr
 ick\, A Literary Journal.\nT\nhe\nFall-Down Effect\nis her debut novel.
LOCATION:Flying Books\, 784 College St.
URL:https://flyingbooks.ca/events
X-SOURCE:Flying Books
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:JOIN US FOR AN AUTHOR SOCIAL WITH NICOLE LOUIE AND EMMA MCKENNA MO
 DERATED BY CHRISTINE J. ERICKSON
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260422T183000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260422T203000
UID:bm-4855120260422@flyingbooks.ca
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://cdn1.bookmanager.com/i/8102716/Nicole_Lo
 uie___Emma_McKenna_Author_Social.jpg?cb=1773949394
DESCRIPTION:[Author Social]\nJoin us for a conversation with Nicole Louie\
 , author of\nOthers Like Me\,\nand Emma McKenna\, author of\nGold Star\n\,
  in conversation with Christine Erickson about what life is like without c
 hildren. Admission is free\, but space is limited. Please RSVP to attend
 .\nOthers Like Me: The Lives of Women Without Children\nis a deeply person
 al exploration of childless and childfree women in their own words.\nIn a 
 world that expects all women to become mothers\, what happens to those who
  circumvent motherhood? Now and throughout history\, women without childre
 n have been misunderstood and even vilified for not conforming to the pres
 criptive path of daughter\, wife\, mother\, whether by choice\, circumstan
 ce\, or ambivalence. But with an increasing number of people choosing to f
 orego children\, Nicole Louie knew she was not alone. As she recounts her 
 own journey toward embracing a life without children\, Louie weaves in sto
 ries from the women around the world she found in her search for community
  and guidance\, from their pasts to their presents to their hopes for the 
 future.\nGold Star\nis\na\ncandid and moving collection from Emma McKenna.
  She explores the multifaceted themes of bodily autonomy\, capturing the e
 mpowerment of queer femme identity.\n\n\nDrawn from the experience of grow
 ing up in poverty in a single-parent home and escaping to the city at the 
 age of sixteen\, these poems look at the physical and emotional implicatio
 ns of trauma but also reveal how being bisexual and disabled can be source
 s of resilience\, joy\, and creativity. Examining the way sexism and sexua
 l violence exist as a spectre throughout the lives of women and girls\,\nG
 old Star\nalso contemplates issues of child abuse and neglect\, reproducti
 ve health\, and the complex decision to be child-free. Never shying away f
 rom the weight of its vital subject matter\, this is an urgent and unflinc
 hing feminist exploration of embodiment.\nABOUT THE AUTHORS:\nNicole Louie
  is a writer and translator based in Ireland. Her essays have appeared in\
 nThe Walrus\, The Guardian\,\nand\nLiterary Hub.\nAnd her curated collecti
 ons of books and movies about women who are not mothers can be found on In
 stagram: @bynicolelouie.\nOthers Like Me: The Lives of Women Without Child
 ren\n(House of Anansi)  is her first book.\nEmma McKenna is a multidiscipl
 inary writer with a passion for women’s histories and narratives. She re
 ceived her PhD in English and Cultural Studies from McMaster University an
 d has published widely on feminist issues. McKenna is also the author of\n
 Chenille or Silk\n\, shortlisted for the 2020 Hamilton Literary Award for 
 Poetry. Born in British Columbia and raised in Alberta\, she lives in the 
 Waterloo Region with her husband and two dogs.\nChristine J. Erickson foun
 ded the New Legacy Institute (NLI) to confront the global imposition and r
 eal-world impact of pronatalist constructs and policy. NLI's mission is to
  advocate for a fundamental re-imagining of social policy\, ensuring equal
  rights and protections across reproductive and relationship experiences.
LOCATION:Flying Books at Neverland\, 371 Queen St. W.
URL:https://flyingbooks.ca/events
X-SOURCE:Flying Books
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:JOIN US FOR AN AUTHOR SOCIAL WITH KERRY CLARE
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260429T183000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260429T203000
UID:bm-4855820260429@flyingbooks.ca
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://cdn1.bookmanager.com/i/8102716/Kerry_Cla
 re_Author_Social.jpg?cb=1773340082
DESCRIPTION:[Author Social]\nJoin us for a conversation with Kerry Clare 
 author of\nDefinitely Thriving\n\, in conversation with Julia Zarankin abo
 ut finding meaning/coming into one's own.  Admission is free\, but space 
 is limited. Please RSVP to attend.\nDefinitely\nThriving\nis a novel abou
 t friendship\, community\, and church jumble sales. It's a celebration of 
 people who are perfectly imperfect\, and all the love\nand support that’
 s required for one woman to make it on her own.\nAfter accidentally-on-pur
 pose exploding her listless marriage by being\ndiscovered in bed with the 
 next-door neighbours\, Clemence Lathbury returns to\nher hometown resolved
  to build a life for herself that is good and substantial\, to\nbecome the
  kind of sensible woman who won’t be distracted by frippery and\nromance
 . It’s supposed to be Eat\, Pray\, Love\, without the love part. But no\
 nwoman is an island\, and soon Clemence finds herself embroiled in\nneighb
 ourhood drama\; beginning a crusade at the local bookshop\; becoming\nadop
 ted by a well-groomed\, one-eyed cat\; and being forced to admit her\nattr
 action to two very different men—each a romantic lead in his own right. 
 But\nhow to choose? And never mind the complications of her quirky family 
 ...\nKERRY CLARE\nis the author of the novels\nAsking for a Friend\n\,\nWa
 iting for a Star\nto Fall\n\, and\nMitzi Bytes\n\; and editor of\nThe M Wo
 rd: Conversations about\nMotherhood\n. Her essays have been nominated for\
 nNational Magazine Awards\n.\nShe edits\n49thShelf.com\n\, a website about
  Canadian books\, and writes about\nbooks and reading on her longtime blog
 \,\nPickle Me This\n. Kerry Clare lives in\nToronto with her family.
LOCATION:Flying Books at Neverland\, 371 Queen St. W.
URL:https://flyingbooks.ca/events
X-SOURCE:Flying Books
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Celebrating New Asian Canadian Novels
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260430T183000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260430T200000
UID:bm-4900520260430@flyingbooks.ca
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://cdn1.bookmanager.com/i/8102716/Book_Laun
 ch_Jane___Leslie.png?cb=1774302283
DESCRIPTION:[Book Signing]\nHouse of Anansi\, Comorant\, and Flying Books 
 are thrilled to to host authors Jane Park (\nInheritance\n) and Leslie Sh
 imotakahara\n(The Breakwater\n) for a conversation and book signing.\nABOU
 T\nINHERTANCE\nA Korean Canadian woman returns to the prairies\, where she
  revisits her childhood and confronts her haunting guilt.\nInheritance\nex
 plores the immigrant experience\, the sacrifices made by both parents and 
 children\, and the way trauma is transferred to the next generation. As An
 ne completes her journey to the past\, she emerges to finally define life 
 on her own terms.\nJane Park\nis a second-generation Korean Canadian write
 r. She is a MacDowell Fellow\, and was a participant in the Banff Centre
 ’s Writing Studio\, and Diaspora Dialogues. She was born in Edmonton\, A
 lberta\, lived in New York City for over a decade\, and now lives in Calga
 ry\, Alberta. Currently\, she is pursuing an MFA at the University of Brit
 ish Columbia. Inheritance is her debut novel.\nABOUT\nTHE BREAKWATER\nA mu
 ltigenerational saga about the long shadow of an unspeakable family secret
 \, culminating in an overdue reunion between rivalrous brothers.  In this
  heartbreaking family story\, two brothers\, both old men not far from dea
 th\, must at last confront long-buried family secrets — and their linger
 ing effects on subsequent generations.\nLeslie Shimotakahara\nis an award-
 winning author of three novels and a memoir\, as well as numerous short fi
 ction and essays. She won the Canada-Japan Literary Prize (2012) and has b
 een shortlisted for the K.M. Hunter Artist Award. Her writing has appeared
  in the\nNational Post\n\,\nWorld Literature Today\,\nand other anthologie
 s and periodicals. She holds a PhD in English from Brown University\, and 
 lives in Toronto with her husband.
LOCATION:Flying Books\, 784 College St.
URL:https://flyingbooks.ca/events
X-SOURCE:Flying Books
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:JOIN US FOR THE LAUNCH OF PRECEDENCE BY PUJITA VERMA
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260505T183000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260505T200000
UID:bm-4908220260505@flyingbooks.ca
DESCRIPTION:[Book Launch]\nJoin Brick Books and Flying Books for the launc
 h of\nPrecedence\nby Pujita Verma\, who will be in conversation with autho
 r Charlie Petch. Book signing to follow.\nABOUT THE BOOK\nGrounded in a re
 cent legal case that crosses borders\,\nPrecedence\noffers an intimate and
  stunningly poised insight into a young woman’s experience leaving home 
 and facing her father in a Canadian courtroom. Pujita Verma’s tender\, h
 opeful voice exposes the shortcomings of the international legal infrastru
 cture in providing recourse to survivors of childhood sexual abuse\, while
  honoring the generations of women who have protected and taught her\, and
  whose sacrifices ultimately put her in the position to speak out publicly
 . What precedents\, Verma asks—legal\, personal\, cultural—do we rewri
 te for ourselves and others each time we act? What does it look like to kn
 ow romantic love\, and come of age\, after coming forward\nABOUT THE AUTHO
 R\nPujita Verma is a poet and illustrator currently living in London\, Ont
 ario. Her work has appeared across the Toronto Transit Commission Network 
 and CBC’s\nThe National.\nShe won awards from the League of Canadian Poe
 ts\, the Toronto Arts & Letters Club Foundation\, and the Eden Mills Write
 r’s Festival\, and was runner-up for the Janice Colbert Poetry Award. Pu
 jita was Mississauga’s Youth Poet Laureate from 2018-2020\, and she stud
 ied Political Science at Western University. As an active member of London
 ’s literary scene\, Pujita is currently serving on the committee for Ant
 ler River Poetry.
LOCATION:Flying Books\, 784 College St.
URL:https://flyingbooks.ca/events
X-SOURCE:Flying Books
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:JOIN US THE LAUNCH OF THE TIME OF THE GREAT SINGING BY ELIZABETH P
 HILIPS
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260512T183000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260512T200000
UID:bm-5019020260512@flyingbooks.ca
DESCRIPTION:[Book Launch]\nFreehand Books and Flying Books is thrilled to 
 host the launch of Elizabeth Philip's new book\,\nThe Time of the Great Si
 nging.\nBooks will be available for sale and signing\n.\nA kinetic new poe
 try collection that sings our astonishment and our fear at how life makes 
 and unmakes us through every love and every grief.\n\n\n\n\nThese poems ar
 e at once plangent and wise\, fired by exacting observation of the changes
  that mark the natural world—the diminishing woods\, the surging birdson
 g in spring–as well as each stage of human life. The poet struggles to u
 nderstand what her experiences mean\, even as a sudden turn—a mother’s
  illness\, a father’s death—sweeps her in an entirely different direct
 ion.\nPhilips writes of “this borrowed ground\,” our trespass on the e
 arth none of us can own. In every movement of these poems as they flow ove
 r rough ground and smooth\, there’s the thrill of discovery\, and the ec
 hoing notes of what we can’t know\, the mystery of changes yet to come.\
 nElizabeth Philips’s first novel\,\nThe Afterlife of Birds\n\, won the C
 ity of Saskatoon Book Award and was a finalist for the Amazon Canada First
  Novel Award. She is the former editor of\nGrain\nmagazine\, and the forme
 r director of the Banff Centre’s Emerging Writers Intensive.\nThe Time o
 f the Great Singing\nis her fifth book of poetry. She lives in Saskatoon.
LOCATION:Flying Books\, 784 College St.
URL:https://flyingbooks.ca/events
X-SOURCE:Flying Books
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:JOIN AGA MAKSIMOWSKA IN CONVERSATION WITH AMY JONES
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260514T183000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260514T200000
UID:bm-4910220260514@flyingbooks.ca
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://cdn1.bookmanager.com/i/8102716/Flying_Bo
 oks_Aga_and_Amy.jpg?cb=1774041660
DESCRIPTION:[Book Signing]\nDundurn Press and Flying Books are excited to 
 have Aga Maksimowska\, author of\nBecalming\n\, in conversation about her 
 book and mentorship with Amy Jones at our College St. location. Book signi
 ng to follow.\nABOUT THE BOOK:\nGosia feels stalled in her life\, but a fa
 mily trip opens her eyes to the life she has … and the life she wants.\n
 \nGosia\, a high school chemistry teacher\, travels to her native Poland t
 o visit her estranged father. Back in Canada\, meanwhile\, her father-in-l
 aw — who has been more of a dad to her than her own — is dying of canc
 er. Away from her routine\, Gosia questions everything in her life\, inclu
 ding her long-term boyfriend\, Peter. She feels stuck in the terrifying ti
 me of early adulthood\, in her first grown-up job while managing student d
 ebt\, monogamy\, and existential dread. Is this really it\, she wonders?\n
 \nGosia’s time in Poland gives her the chance to examine her life\, and 
 she finds herself pulled homeward to Canada\, where she faces the fact tha
 t Peter’s father — like her own — is far from perfect. Can she love 
 despite betrayal? Can she find hope in her fiery\, complex love for Peter?
  Is there something more to this life that she didn’t even realize she h
 ad?\n\nBecalming tells the story of two people realizing that happily ever
  after is not something to be but something to continue to explore\, throu
 gh adversity and outrage\, tragedy and inspiration\, and love.\nABOUT THE 
 AUTHOR\nAga Maksimowska is a writer whose debut novel\nGiant\,\nabout prem
 ature sexual development and the fall of Communism in Poland\, was shortli
 sted for the Toronto Book Award. Her writing has appeared in\nPolish[ed]: 
 Poland Rooted in Canadian Fiction\, Brick\,\nt\nhe Globe and Mail\,\nand o
 thers. Becalming is her second novel. She lives in Toronto.
LOCATION:Flying Books\, 784 College St.
URL:https://flyingbooks.ca/events
X-SOURCE:Flying Books
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:JOIN US FOR THE LAUNCH OF SMALLER ANIMALS
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260519T183000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260519T200000
UID:bm-4793220260519@flyingbooks.ca
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://cdn1.bookmanager.com/i/8102716/unnamed.j
 pg?cb=1773254238
DESCRIPTION:[Book Launch]\nJoin us for an evening of discussion on\nSmalle
 r Animals\n\, the debut novel by Canadian author Carter Vance\, in convers
 ation with Doug Vidal-Hernandez.\nAdam Brinkert was raised a world apart f
 rom the lights of Ottawa and the din of politics\, in a small city in Nort
 hern Ontario. Pursuing justice and a way to make things better for the peo
 ple he grew up with\, he became an assistant to a Member of Parliament\, l
 iving his youth in the offices and hallways of power. But\, as he grows to
 wards his 30s\, he begins to doubt what it was all for\; were his experien
 ces all merely for self-aggrandizement and not the greater good?\n\nTwists
  of fate and slights of political hand will test Adam’s belief in himsel
 f\, and what he believes is right\, while he navigates the landscape of a 
 country\, and a world\, that is changing rapidly. All the while\, he strug
 gles to define his relationships with the people around him\, including hi
 s erstwhile friend-cum-political rival Truss and his ex-girlfriend and co-
 worker Kathleen. Adam’s journey will take him across the county and back
  to his home\, searching for a spark to guide him where he truly belongs.\
 nSmaller Animals i\ns a story of living\, loving and growing up on Parliam
 ent Hill that introduces a powerful new voice in Canadian literature.\nCar
 ter Vance is a writer and poet originally from Cobourg\, Ontario\, current
 ly a resident in Gatineau\, Quebec. His work has appeared in such publicat
 ions as\nThe Smart Set\, Contemporary Verse 2\nand\nA Midwestern Review\,\
 namongst others.\nSmaller Animals\nis his first novel\, following two poet
 ry collections.\n\nCarter has worked as a researcher and policy analyst wi
 th government and non-profit organizations in Canada\, the United Kingdom\
 , Dominica and Indonesia. He was a staffer for several members of Parliame
 nt\, including the Opposition House Leader in 2014 and also worked in the 
 Senate of Canada.\nDoug Vidal-Hernández was a political staffer at the Na
 tional Office of the Liberal Party of Canada and worked through the 2015 n
 ational campaign as part of a rapid response team providing local candidat
 es with policy support. He then became part of the caucus services team at
  the Liberal Research Bureau\, supporting parliamentarians and their polit
 ical staff. \n\nNow\, as a recovered staffer he works at Code for Canada\,
  a national non profit focused on creating strong digital public services\
 , accessible and inclusive design and responsible AI use.
LOCATION:Flying Books\, 784 College St.
URL:https://flyingbooks.ca/events
X-SOURCE:Flying Books
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:JOIN US FOR THE LAUNCH OF LATERAL SWAY BY HANNAH KARPINSKI
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260521T183000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260521T200000
UID:bm-5027220260521@flyingbooks.ca
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://cdn1.bookmanager.com/i/8102716/HK.JPG?cb
 =1775601294
DESCRIPTION:[Book Launch]\nPlease join Metatron and Flying Books for the l
 aunch of Hannah Karpinski’s new book\,\nLateral Sway.\nHannah will be jo
 ined by Jowita Bydlowska\, author of\nUnshaming.\nThe evening will be host
 ed by Ashley Obscura. Book signing to follow.\nMoving through queer intima
 cy\, memory\, and displacement\, the poems in this collection trace what i
 t means to be pulled off-course—towards others\, towards language\, towa
 rds fleeting forms of belonging. Fragmentary and tender\,\nLateral Sway\no
 ffers an account of how connections survive across bodies\, borders\, and 
 time.\nHannah Karpinski is a lesbian Canadian poet from Tkaronto/Toronto. 
 Diving into intimate personal archives and collective memory\, she writes 
 about queer friendship and queer desire. You can find her poems in\nCommo 
 Mag\,\nVoicemail Poem\ns\n\,\nGhost City Press’ My Loves: Digital Anthol
 ogy of Queer Love Poems\,\nand elsewhere.\nLateral Sway\nis her first book
 .
LOCATION:Flying Books\, 784 College St.
URL:https://flyingbooks.ca/events
X-SOURCE:Flying Books
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:JOIN US FOR THE LAUNCH OF TEMPORARY PALACES BY JEFF MILLER
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260525T183000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260525T200000
UID:bm-4878620260525@flyingbooks.ca
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://cdn1.bookmanager.com/i/8102716/May_25_Fl
 ying_Books.JPG?cb=1773686253
DESCRIPTION:[Book Launch]\nJoin House of Anansi and Flying Books to celebr
 ate the launch of\nTemporary Palace\ns by Jeff Miller. Jeff will be joined
  by authors Niko Stratis and Emma Healey.\n"A plainspoken\, punk-rock hymn
  … This is a book that will pick you up off the floor of a mosh pit and 
 wrap you in its arms." —Sean Michaels\nIn the fevered summer of 2001\, c
 harismatic activist Rob and his collective set up a squat in an abandoned 
 house. His bandmate and lover\, Ben\, watches anxiously as his own plans a
 re threatened by Rob’s choice of radical politics over music. Meanwhile\
 , photographer Alex finds herself torn between documenting the chaos of th
 e scene and saving the friendship that binds them together. When the polic
 e break up the squat\, Rob vanishes\, and the dream dies.\n\nTen years lat
 er\, Alex and Ben find each other again—she’s conquering Montreal’s 
 contemporary art world\, he’s running a thriving restaurant in Ottawa. B
 ut their success feels hollow. As they excavate their shared past\, they m
 ust confront the ghost of Rob’s disappearance and the trauma that pushed
  them apart.\n\nPulsing with the raw energy of basement punk shows and DIY
  creativity\, late-night manifestos and first heartbreaks\,\nTemporary Pal
 aces\nis a blazing debut that captures a generation caught between idealis
 m and survival\, art and activism\, the dreams that define us and the comp
 romises that save us.\nJEFF MILLER is the author of the award-winning crea
 tive nonfiction collection\nGhost Pine:\nA\nll Stories True.\nHis stories 
 have appeared in several anthologies\, and he frequently publishes critici
 sm. Jeff holds an MFA from the University of British Columbia and lives in
  Nova Scotia.
LOCATION:Flying Books\, 784 College St.
URL:https://flyingbooks.ca/events
X-SOURCE:Flying Books
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:FOUR POETS: LAURIE D. GRAHAM\, BARBARA TRAN\, KEVIN IRIE\, RONNA B
 LOOM
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260527T183000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260527T200000
UID:bm-5013320260527@flyingbooks.ca
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://cdn1.bookmanager.com/i/8102716/POET.png?
 cb=1775483296
DESCRIPTION:[Book Launch]\nJoin four award-winning poets as they read from
  their newest books\nand discuss their work and the art and craft of poetr
 y. Books will be\navailable for sale and signing.\nLaurie D. Graham is a p
 oet\, an editor\, and the publisher of\nBrick\nmagazine. Her newest book i
 s\nCalling It Back to Me\n(McClelland &\nStewart).\nBarbara Tran’s debut
  poetry book\,\nPrecedented Parroting\n(Palimpsest Press)\, was selected a
 s a finalist for the Governor\nGeneral’s Literary Award and the Fred Cog
 swell Award for\nExcellence in Poetry.\nKevin Irie’s newest book is\nEva
 cuations\n(University of Alberta\nPress). His works have been translated i
 nto Spanish\, French\, and\nJapanese\, and his book\,\nViewing Tom Thomson
 : A Minority Report\,\nwas a finalist for the Acorn-Plantos Award and the 
 Toronto Book\nAward.\nRonna Bloom is the author of eight books of poetry\,
  most recently\nIn a Riptide\n(\nBrick Books). Her work has been broadcast
  on the CBC\,\nrecorded by the Canadian National Institute for the Blind\,
  translated\ninto Bangla and Chinese\, and shortlisted for several Canadia
 n literary\nawards.
LOCATION:Flying Books\, 784 College St.
URL:https://flyingbooks.ca/events
X-SOURCE:Flying Books
END:VEVENT
END:VCALENDAR
